Hi Mickey, Agree with you. the external_v4_ip or v6 will be populated from this new api. I did not try to change the definition of the existed VPN  tables.
/v2.0/routers/​{router_id}​/add_router_interface is used to add the private network gateway port port, not the external gateway port. 
Neutron use the API /v2.0/routers with below request body to add external gateway port:
{
   "router": {
      "external_gateway_info": {
         "network_id": "8ca37218-28ff-41cb-9b10-039601ea7e6b"
      }
   }
}

if we add to existing  /v2.0/vpn/vpnservices api with the port UUID, then customer have to create the port firstly and have to configure it per vpn services. If there are more one vpn service bound with one router, customer need to do  multiple configuration. There are another case is what will happen if customer configures different port for two different vpn services which is bound with a same router?

So I still think it is better to just to specify the external network UUID, then the plugin will automatically create it with the UUID. That is same as what the router external gateway is doing.

And I think it is better to bind the external network with the router id, not the vpn services id. It is also same as vpn use router external gateway IP address.

that is why I just added some extended attribute with the router. Anyway, if you like, I could change this API URL to /v2.0/vpn/external_port 
but as I know, the new URL, there will be 5 API for any new URL:POST/PUT/DELETE/GET/LIST. Do we really need so many APIs.

I think after the customer configure the vpn external IP/Port, VPN plugin will schedule a new agent and create the namespace and bind the port/ip to the namespace. This is what the l3-agent was doing.
